I wanted to expand on something tokumaru touched on:<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />... From looking at your code, I see that you have an empty main loop and all the program logic runs in the NMI handler. This is fine, as long as you perform all the PPU updates first (because those MUST be performed during VBlank) and then run the program logic. ...<br /></div><br />It's important to understand that although this is completely fine to do (especially when starting out), VBlank itself lasts approximately ~2250 CPU cycles (that nesdev Wiki link tokumaru provided mentions this).  Be sure to take loops and other things that happen within your code (within NMI) into consideration when developing something this way.<br /><br />Basically the idea is: if there's "stuff" you can safely do outside of VBlank, do it outside of VBlank.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3">koitsu</a> — Sat Jan 15, 2011 3:49 pm</p><hr />
